05249nam a22007335i 9781501503870DE-B159720210202111235.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210202t20172017gw     fo  d z      chi d  a97815015038707 a10.1515/97815015038702doi  a(DE-B1597)461836  a(OCoLC)999369785  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 achi  agwcDE 4aPL2664.J8bA2 2017 7aLIT0080002bisacsh04a895.11/22231 aOwen, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Poetry of Ruan Ji and Xi Kang /cWendy Swartz, Stephen Owen; Ding Xiang Warner, Xiaofei Tian. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (VI, 406 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLibrary of Chinese Humanities00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tPart 1: The Poetry of Ruan Ji (210-263) -- tIntroduction -- tSinging My Cares -- tThe Poetic Expositions ( fu) -- tAbbreviations -- tAdditional Notes -- tPart 2: The Poetry of Xi Kang (ca. 223 - ca. 262) -- tIntroduction -- tPoems -- tAdditional Notes -- tModern Editions Cited0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe poetry of Ruan Ji has been previously translated several times, with one fully scholarly translation of both the poetry and the Fu (poetic expositions). The present translation not only provides a facing page critical Chinese text, it addresses two problems that have been ignored or not adequately treated in earlier works. First, it traces the history of the current text. The rather serious problems with this text will be, if not soluble, at least visible. Second, translations have been shaped by the anachronistic assumption that Ruan Ji was loyal to the declining Wei dynasty, when actual power had been taken by the Suma family, who founded the Jin dynasty after Ruan Ji's death. The introduction shows how and when that assumption took full shape five centuries after Ruan Ji lived and why it is not tenable. This leads to a different kind of translation, closer to what a contemporary reader might have understood and far less certain than referring it to some political event. The Poetry of Xi Kang presents a complete scholarly translation of his poetic works (including "Rhapsody on the Zither") alongside the original texts. Many of Xi Kang's poems are difficult and most are laden with allusions and "ations, adding another level of challenge to interpretation. Basic explanatory notes are provided. The translations are based on the critical modern edition of Xi Kang's work by Dai Mingyang, generally considered to be the best edition available. Important editions by Lu Xun and Lu Qinli are consulted on matters of variants, arrangement, and interpretation.  afunded by The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn Chinese.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aChinese poetryvPhilosophy. 0aChinese poetryy220-589vTranslations into English. 0aChinese poetry. 4aChinesisch. 4aGedichte. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh  aChinese Literature.  aEarly Medieval Chinese Poetry.  aRuan Ji.  aXi Kang.1 aSwartz, Wendy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTian, Xiaofei, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWarner, Ding Xiang, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt2 aThe Andrew W. Mellon Foundationefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Col